        "id": 1814393,
        "name": "George Chadwick",
        "username": "George_Chadwick",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/ecae2f/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2015-12-15T19:45:55.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>2004 Potel Gaudichots. If I knew nothing about greenness in 2004s I never would have thought about flaws in this. Deep complex and unique. There is a possible green herbal thing that should only bother you if you\u2019re sick of greenness in 2004 the way depressingly overbretty wines have lowered my Brett tolerance.<br>\nMy greenness palate: conversely my first 2004, before I knew anything about the vintage, was an Anne Gros Richebourg a close friend was proud of bringing. I announced loudly that it tasted of bug spray and caustic chemicals drowning out any fruit. Nice guy huh. But the point is I\u2019m not a fan of 2004 greenness and I still loved the Potel.</p>\n<p>Two green 2004s I\u2019ve liked, both tasted before greenness had a chance to mellow so they should be even better now, are Ponsot CdlR and Roty ChCh. Big fruit and great structure can relegate the green to a mere component.</p>\n<p>If Lignier 2004s are OK then the LA Lignier Morey Prem Cru is a ridiculous bargain right now at $50. (Boring part omitted about why 2004 and 2005 LA Lignier\u2019s are special and underpriced but only those years). Ordered some, will report.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 9,
