      {
        "id": 1817955,
        "name": "A. So",
        "username": "A_So",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/a_so/{size}/1582_2.png",
        "created_at": "2015-12-20T16:05:07.000Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"Stuart BeauneHead Niemtzow\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n Stuart BeauneHead Niemtzow:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>This just reaffirms that tasting notes on 2004s are more about the taster than the wines. (And, enjoyable wines can be mostly about the taster\u2019s genetic limitations.)</p>\n<p>I convinced myself of this a long time ago\u2026and\u2026stay off 2004 threads as a result\u2026i hardly even read them\u2026but since Jeremy Holmes stirred me to respond on the other 2004 thread happening here\u2026I read this one\u2026and\u2026nothing has changed, I see. People still think they are talking about the wines when they enjoy 2004s\u2026and don\u2019t realize though they might be, they are probably talking more about their own limitations/perceptions. Mind boggling\u2026and always has been.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>Um\u2026 is there some sort of absolute scale through which to\u2026evaluate wines\u2026 besides one\u2019s own personal experience with a bottle\u2026? Whatever your genetics\u2026if it tastes like shitty wine\u2026it\u2019s shitty wine.</p>",
